<a href="javascript:card_browser(73)">Goblin Scavengers</a> x4<br>
Goblin Scrabbler<br>
Goblin Flankers x2<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(80)">Goblin Warrior</a><br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(86)">Moria Scout</a> x4<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(94)">Troll&#39;s Keyward</a> x2<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(125)">Ulaire Enquea, Lieutenant of Morgul</a><br>
<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(312)">Cave Troll of Moria, Scourge of the Black Pit</a> x3<br>
The Balrog, Flame of Udun<br>
<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(313)">Cave Troll&#39;s Hammer</a><br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(75)">Goblin Scimitar</a> x4<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(85)">Moria Axe</a><br>
<br>
Goblin <a href="javascript:card_browser(303)">Armor</a>y x4<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(78)">Goblin Swarms</a> x3<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(90)">Relics of Moria</a> x2<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(91)">They Are Coming</a> x3    </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Strategy</Font></TD><TD> </TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN="2" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="bfont"> <b>EDIT------------------------</b><br>
Just to counter some of the reviews here, Saruman&#39;s Power may destroy Promises but not Hobbits. The fact remains: he can&#39;t get rid of Mithril Coat. The tales are really not that useful against Isengard except for Consorting, and even then as you&#39;ll see below, more copies will be added. As for Promises, if the Isengard player waits for you to throw 4 Promises before playing Power, he would have held it a long time, affecting the performance of his whole deck. Isengard is also weak in the sense that unless they stick in the odd Tower Assasin, your allies are not getting touched. Wounds? Damage +1? Heal! Believe me, I use Uruks and I hate going up against Hobbits.<br>
<br>
Some modifications:<br>
<br>
A Talent for Not Being Seen x2<br>
Consorting With Wizards x3<br>
Hobbit Party Guest x3<br>
<br>
We&#39;re taking out all copies of the Red Book here. I put it in for fun and really, it sucks. Consorting &#39;cause it&#39;s that much better. We&#39;re also taking out 1 Practically as the exertion is rather painful at times, and Talent is too important to only have one. One more Party Guest &#39;cause playtests have shown the wounds to be a little unmanageable at times.<br>
<br>
And yes, I do recognise the need one more Hobbit Sword, but have no idea what to replace it with, perhaps the Intuition.<br>
<br>
As for shadow, never taking out the Troll. Sure, he may not fit that nicely into a swarm but if you are purely focusing on swarms, you must consistently outnumber him. I have seen many Moria decks unable to touch the opponent without Troll. Troll kills, period.<br>
<br>
<b>EDIT------------------------------</b><br>
<br>
<br>
This is one of my favourite decks. The card-economy and the just-play-it style of Hobbits works very well with Moria. The hobbits are designed to walk slowly (they can run if needed), as it is important to go through all 86 cards in your deck. The shadow is consistent, with multiples of the vital conditions to work the swarm every turn once he enters Moria, and a few techs for discussion later.<br>
<br><br>
<br>
<br><br>
First off, bid around 6. That is the neutral number, so maybe 5 if you know they&#39;re playing Nazgul. Pippin removes 1 immediately, and Sam removes to 3. Try not to exhaust him first-turn, or your Promises will be useless and Hate can screw you fast.<br>
<br><br>
<br>
<br><br>
Start first, yes, you are foregoing the safety of Buckleberry Ferry (unless you draw one of the 2 Thror&#39;s Map first-turn) to get Bilbo out via Hobbiton Party Field. Bilbo not only removes important conditions, but Practically Everyone Was Invited is a very efficient card to get every Hobbit ally out for the family photo, and really, I would rather stick 2 of these in than 2 more Bilbos to draw. Besides, Well-Spoken Gentlehobbit is more suited to playing at the start, unlike Retired Adventurer, which is more efficient late-game.<br>
<br><br>
<br>
<br><br>
Watch the twilight pool unless you have the Intuitions, Stealths etc. Merry, Friend to Sam is a very effective companion and can get you out of sticky situations early. (face it, 3 strength is overwhelm-fodder).<br>
<br><br>
<br>
<br><br>
The rest of the game is straightforward. 4 Promises, big load of allies and powerful events. You know what to do with Hobbit decks.<br>
<br><br>
<br>
<br><br>
Against Nazgul, you may get in trouble early on so be careful, but later on, laugh at him with O Elbereth and Filibert. Be sure to remove Blade Tips and Black Breaths from his support area BEFORE they come flying at you (you can&#39;t remove them from companions). Black Breath is the hotspot, as your Hobbit allies can neutralise Blade Tip. Watch out too for Their Power is in Terror, use Sting wisely.<br>
<br><br>
<br>
<br><br>
Against Isengard, you have your easiest match-up. Just get 4 Promises, Sting, Bounder and Mithril Coat out and there you have it, Frodo with 10 strength un-boosted, and needs 30 to overwhelm, and he only takes 1 wound, and the Uruks may be Beyond the Height of Men but they are not taller than Frodo! (can&#39;t discard Mithril Coat). Frodo is simply indestructible and is more than capable of taking on 4 or 5 Uruks at Site 9.<br>
<br><br>
<br>
<br><br>
Against Moria, Stealths and Intuitions bail you out early, and late-game, your hobbit-protection should help. What is really annoying is Throw Yourself in Next Time as Bilbo can&#39;t get rid of it, but fortunately, that card isn&#39;t seeing much play (I love that card)<br>
<br><br>
<br>
<br><br>
Against Sauron, choke him with Sting and Consorting. He wounds you? Remove. Just look out for Tower Assasin (and look out for stupid opponents who try to wound Bilbo + Consorting with him). Sting is big here too, obviously.<br>
<br><br>
<br>
<br><br>
For shadow, it is straightforward. 4 Armories go in every deck. 3 Swarms as it wins games. 3 They are Coming for early card-advantage. 2 Relics of Moria as a supplement to Goblin Scavengers, and the twilight-adder from hell if you get 4 Armories out. The great number of these cards means that if Gandalf Sleeps, I can replace the conditions very quickly. Never let out more than 2 Armories at once against anti-condition decks though, or you will be in trouble without them. 2 Armories are needed to at least balance out Relics.<br>
<br><br>
<br>
<br><br>
4 Runners, 4 Scouts, 4 Scavengers and 4 Scimitars also go in without doubt. 2 Backstabbers for that intelligent play when you see you&#39;re outnumbering him. 3 Cave Trolls to slow him down or kill, and 2 Keywards to bring him out. I included Hammer (recycle with Relics) but not Chain, as the combo is too hard to pull off, and I&#39;d much prefer Chain with the combo I&#39;ll discuss later on. Moria Axe is for Flankers (a possible 17 strength AND Damage +1, half the size of Cave Troll) and Keyward, and if you are really desperate, Moria Scout. Flankers are so much better than Patrol Troop, simply because once they go on Swarms, they can actually be played, and may even deter double-moves. The numbers of Goblin Warrior and Scrabbler are to be modified according to your meta-game, though it is always advisable to use at least 1 Warrior to get rid of Thrarin and Greatest Kingdom of My People, and its perpetuity with They are Coming can totally screw up a Gloin Tale Beat-Up-the-Balrog deck. Enquea is vital in every Moria deck to safeguard against Nine Walkers decks.<br>
<br><br>
<br>
<br><br>
Currently, what I am looking to change, purely in the interest of amusement and not neccessarily efficiency, is to remove the Flankers, Axe and Backstabbers for Spearmen and Goblin Spear. Spearman will then be Damage +2 in any skirmish unlike the Stabber, not to say how Goblin Spear can be used on both Balrog and Cave Troll (recycled by Relics), and thus can pave the way for Troll&#39;s Chain to be added in as you can add Spear + Chain to the Troll if Hammer is not out for overwhelming time, and they may even add a few burdens to draw with Summit of Amon Hen (change to that due to the lack of Flankers) or for Enquea to wreak havogully-boonterested yet, though i&#39;ve always been interested in the potential of Goblin Spearman + Spear + Moria Stairway, phwoar!<br>
<br><br>
<br>
<br><br>
For sites, like I said, Hobbiton Party Field is so important I&#39;m foregoing Woods, Bag End and such. Buckleberry is for the chance where I get Thror&#39;s Map in my opening hand or lose the opening bid. Frodo&#39;s Bedroom as it fuels card advantage, and is really the only useful site here (you don&#39;t want opponents removing twilight with Council Courtyard before entering Moria). Moria Stairway is my favourite, but it all depends on you cycling through your deck fast enough to get something big here. Flankers + Moria Axe is Damage +2, and Troll is an unbelieve Damage +3 with Hammer. Try to give him your most hospitable welcome to Moria. I choose Valley of the Silverlode over Dimrill Dale...just personal preference there. Anduin Wilderland not just because it screws other decks, but it&#39;s the only suitable site for you. You&#39;d better have Map out when you move to Site 7. Shores for Moria to swarm, and Emyn Muil over Summit, because a fierce Flankers or Keyward can often turn the game around. (i.e. your opponent must have companions surviving the normal skirmish swarm)<br>
<br><br>
<br>
<br><br>
Enjoy. This is my usual deck on Apprentice and unbeaten thus far, but I just can&#39;t build it in real life. Where the hell do you get Goblin Armories nowadays???  </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP" COLSPAN="2"><font class="bfont"> <a href="/lotr/decks/decks.php">Back to Decks Directory</a> | <A HREF="/lotr/decks/decks.php?reviews=22983"> Read Reviews </A> | <a href="deckprint.php?deck=22983" TARGET="BLANK_"> Printer Friendly</a></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE><a name="review"></a><font class="h2font">In order to review decks you must be a registered member. <A href="/lotr/main/join.php">Sign up for free!</A></font></font></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_09.gif"></td></tr>
